  "prompt": "Why are so many questions are asked anonymously in Quora nowadays?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why many users choose to ask questions anonymously on Quora:\n\n1. **Privacy Concerns**: Users may want to keep their identity private, especially when asking about sensitive, personal, or controversial topics. Anonymity allows them to seek advice or information without revealing their identity.\n\n2. **Avoiding Judgment**: Some questions might be embarrassing or socially awkward. By asking anonymously, users can avoid potential judgment or stigma from their peers or the community.\n\n3. **Professional Concerns**: People may worry that asking certain questions could affect their professional reputation, especially if the question is related to their job, career, or industry.\n\n4. **Fear of Backlash**: In cases where questions touch on political, religious, or polarizing issues, users may fear backlash, harassment, or negative reactions from others if they are identified.\n\n5. **Exploring Taboo Topics**: Questions about taboo subjects, such as mental health, relationships, or personal struggles, are often asked anonymously to encourage honest and open responses without personal repercussions.\n\n6. **Experimentation**: Some users might test the waters with hypothetical or theoretical questions without wanting to be associated with the topic personally.\n\n7. **Creating Distance**: Anonymity can help users separate their personal life from their online activity, maintaining a boundary between their Quora interactions and their offline identity.\n\nQuora\u2019s anonymity feature provides a safe space for users to ask questions they might not otherwise feel comfortable posing openly. This can lead to more diverse and candid discussions on the platform.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
